data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with specific MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs generic "was false" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Returns the element directly; clear failure if 0 or 2+ match |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` line is fine staying as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in assertion for "all items match predicate." If you want a better failure message there, you could flip it:

```csharp
var inactive = users.Where(u => !u.IsActive).ToList();
Assert.IsEmpty(inactive);
```

This way a failure lists the offending items instead of just saying "false."
